What you need to know:

The chemicals used to treat livestock against ticks and fleas are called acaricides because they kill ticks and mites, which belong to the scientific sub-class called acari.Most of the chemicals also kill fleas which belong to the class insects. Incidentally, not all acaricides also kill fleas.The washing technique and frequency of washing also determine the effectiveness of an acaricide. Animals should be washed once per week.In Kenya, studies have shown that pastoral communities have often been affected by Q-fever but the disease is mostly misdiagnosed or not detected.